Problem 1.

1. Split the data into a training set and a test set. Using out-of-state tuition as the response and the other variables as the predictors, perform forward stepwise selection on the training set in order to identify the best 7 term model.

  • Using forward stepwise regressoion the best 7 term model is one which includes Private, Room.Board, Personal, Terminal, Perc.Alumni, Expend, and Grad.Rate.
library(ISLR)
library(leaps)
library(splines)
library(boot)
library(gam)

attach(College)
x=model.matrix(Outstate~.,College)[,-1]
y=Outstate

set.seed(1)
train=sample(1:nrow(x), nrow(x)/2)
test=(-train)
y.test=y[test]

regfit.fwd = regsubsets(Outstate~., data=College[train,] ,nvmax=7,method="forward")
reg.summary = summary(regfit.fwd)
coef(regfit.fwd, 7)

3. Fit cubic splines to each of the bivariate relationships identiﬁed in (2) and overlay the ﬁts on new graphs of just these variables. Be sure specify how many knots you want. Comment on whether these ﬁts aﬀect your answer to (2).

  • Using the validation approach for the Personal variable we get an optimal number of knots equal to 2. Using 5-fold CV we see that 4 knots is only marginally better than using 1 knot so we will use the less complex model and choose 1.
  • For the Terminal variable every level of knots from 0-5 results in an mse that is almost equal to the others, The 5 fold CV reccomends the model with 5 knots but it is hardly better than a model with 0 knots. I chose to just fit a cubic spline with 2 knots since the MSE was minutely larger than a model with 0 knots and not as wonky as the model with 5 knots.
  • For the Expend Variable I found the optimal number of knots to be 2 using 5 fold cross validation. From the resulting fit I think our initial ideas of non-linearity have been largely confirmed.
  • For the Grad Rate variable a model with 1 knot was found to be optimal via 5 fold CV. These fits have confirmed my answer to 2.
PersonalLims=range(Personal)
Personal.grid=seq(from=PersonalLims[1],to=PersonalLims[2])

#knots=2
model.err=NULL
for(i in 3:8){
fit=lm(Outstate~bs(Personal,df=i),data=College[train,])
pred=predict(fit, newdata = list(Personal=Personal.grid))
model.err = c(model.err, mean((Outstate[test]-pred)^2))
}

4. Fit a GAM on the training data, using out-of-state tuition as the response and the features selected in the previous steps as the predictors. Plot the results, and explain your ﬁndings.

  • From the plots we can see that our model suggest that holding Pct. Faculty with a terminal degree, Instructional expenditure per student, and Graduation rate fixed, that as estimated personal spending increases Out of state tuition decreases convexly and then changes to a linear relationship.
  • For the terminal variable we can interpret its plot as holding all else constant as the number of terminal degrees held at a university increases the out of state tuition decreases in a cubic fashion, increasing its slope durastically for larger values of terminal.
  • For the expenditure per student we can see that our model suggest that as this increases Out of state tuition rises rapidly before leveling off and not changing much after a certain level is reached, holding all else equal in the model.
  • The Grad.Rate variables plot suggest that as the graduation rate increases the out of state tuition will rise in a mild cubic fashion before decreasing slightly at very high levels of graduation rates.
gam1 = gam(Outstate~bs(Personal, df=4) + bs(Terminal, df=5) + bs(Expend, df=6) + bs(Grad.Rate, df=4), data=College[train,])
plot(gam1)

5. Apply the model to the test set and report the test error

g.preds = predict(gam1, newdata=College[test,])

8. Use the lm() function to perform a multiple linear regression with mpg as the response and all other variables except name as the predictors. Use the summary() function to print the results. Comment on the output in the following ways:

  • a) Is there a relationship between the predictors and the response?
    • For some of the variables it appears that there is indeed a relationship, however quite a few coefficient estimates are close to 0 and non significant in this model, suggesting not all predictors have a linear relationship with the response.
  • b) Which predictors appear to have a statistically signiﬁcant relationship to the response?
    • Displacement, Weight, Year, and Origin all appear to be significantly different from 0.
  • c) What does the coeﬃcient for year suggest?
    • The coefficient on year suggest that a car that was built this year will get on average .75 mpg more than a similar vehicle from the year prior.

9. Produce diagnostic plots of the linear regression ﬁt. Comment on any problems you see with the ﬁt. Do the residual plots suggest any unusually large outliers? Does the leverage plot identify any observations with unusually high leverage?

  • It appears that our assumption of linearity may be violated as seen in the Residuals vs. Fitted plot, we can see a clear bowing effect in the middle, perhaps a transformation or use of GAM could help this solve this issue.
  • From our Scale-Location plot we can see that there are not any major signs of heteroskedasticity
  • Observation 323, 326, and 327 appear to be unusually large outliers.
  • Observation 327, 394, and 14 appear to show signs of high leverage.

11. With your ﬁnal model from (10), perform a bootstrap procedure to estimate the standard errors of your model coeﬃcients. Comment on how the results compare to your previous output.

  • It appears that the regression output was underestimating the standard errors, the bootstrapped estimates are all slightly larger than the standard errors obtained from the previous regression output.
boot.fn=function(data,index){
return(coef(lm(mpg~(.-name)^2, data=Auto,subset=index)))
}

set.seed(1)
boots = boot(Auto,boot.fn,1000)
boots
